{"id":14880759,"mediaExerciseId":"edb30281-ba18-49ee-80c3-e275b0df7697","exerciseName":"8","chapterName":"2","chapterTitle":"Financial Statements, Taxes, and Cash Flow","groupId":612265,"groupTitle":"Questions and Problems","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":43,"solutions":[{"id":5901442,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"This exercise requires us to compute for the cash flow to creditor of Kerber's Tennis Shop.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"Let's first define cash flow to creditors.\n\n**Cash Flow to Creditors** s the amount of money that is paid to the debt holders during an accounting period.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":66,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/18/32751921587d29e8de9efd4e9fd3bae0/ff78ef3b114c737deba4ac0d073a6237/lateximg_large.png","width":994},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/18/32751921587d29e8de9efd4e9fd3bae0/ff78ef3b114c737deba4ac0d073a6237/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"Cash Flow to Creditors is computed as follows:\n\n$$ \\begin{aligned}\n\\text{Cash Flow to Creditors} &= \\text{Interest Paid} - {\\text{Net New Borrowings}}\\\\[1pt]\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\n\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":103,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/18/32751921587d29e8de9efd4e9fd3bae0/ef47d8a2eab380535aee9aca1e776091/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":53,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/18/32751921587d29e8de9efd4e9fd3bae0/ef47d8a2eab380535aee9aca1e776091/lateximg.png","width":496}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"Let's identify the given amounts in the problem.\n\n| |Amounts ($) | \n|--|--:| \n| Long-term debt, 2017| 1,870,000| \n|Long-term debt, 2018| 2,210,000 | \n|Interest Expense |255,000 | \n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":102,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/18/32751921587d29e8de9efd4e9fd3bae0/418f69c28b060aa30a6bed6cd4cbdafd/lateximg_large.png","width":914},"regular":{"height":52,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/18/32751921587d29e8de9efd4e9fd3bae0/418f69c28b060aa30a6bed6cd4cbdafd/lateximg.png","width":457}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"Before we compute for the cash flow to creditors, we need to compute first the net new borrowings using the formula below:\n\n $$ \\begin{aligned}\n\\text{Net New Borrowings} &= \\text{Long-term debt 2018} - {\\text{Long-term debt 2017}}\\\\[5pt]\n&= \\text{\\$2,210,000} - {\\text{1,870,000}}\\\\[5pt]\n&= \\underline{\\underline{\\textbf{\\$340,000}}}\n\\end{aligned}$$\n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5},{"columns":[{"text":"Now that we have computed the net new borrowings , let's now compute for the cash flow to creditors using the equation in step 3.\n\n$$ \\begin{aligned}\n\\text{Cash Flow to Creditors} &= \\text{Interest Paid} - {\\text{Net New Borrowings}}\\\\[5pt]\n&= \\text{\\$255,000} - {\\text{340,000}}\\\\[5pt]\n&= \\underline{\\underline{\\textbf{(\\$85,000)}}}\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\nTherefore, the cash flow to creditor of Kerber's Tennis Shop is **-$85,000**.\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":293,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/18/32751921587d29e8de9efd4e9fd3bae0/22fbcf9c3cc4271dd5eb74602ded50d2/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":148,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/18/32751921587d29e8de9efd4e9fd3bae0/22fbcf9c3cc4271dd5eb74602ded50d2/lateximg.png","width":497}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":6}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"0cb5c1f2-ca6c-4bde-af15-10393d9d78f9","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":6}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14880760,"exerciseName":"9","page":43,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"a373d7f3-3e17-4d0a-8b55-ce148e27f27e","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-2-questions-and-problems-9-a373d7f3-3e17-4d0a-8b55-ce148e27f27e"},{"id":14880761,"exerciseName":"10","page":44,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"8a814dc3-58f5-465e-b51c-c857e57877e4","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-2-questions-and-problems-10-8a814dc3-58f5-465e-b51c-c857e57877e4"}],"previousExercises":[{"id":14880758,"exerciseName":"7","page":43,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"8328b85b-f872-4963-9a3a-7008aaa7deef","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-2-questions-and-problems-7-8328b85b-f872-4963-9a3a-7008aaa7deef"},{"id":14880757,"exerciseName":"6","page":43,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"58735d85-1b22-4a77-abe5-1f84ff496643","_webUrl":"htt